         b'\t<h2>Summary of IFIPTM&#039;08 conference sessions</h2>\n\n\t\t\t'
         b'<div class="entry">\n\t\t\t\t<p style="0cm;">The <a href="http://'
         b'www.ntnu.no/videre/konferanse/IFIPTM08/index.html" target="_self">IF'
         b'IP trust management conference</a>, this year joined for the second '
         b'time with the Privacy, Security and Trust (PST) conference, was held'
         b' in June 18th &#8211; 20th in Trondheim, Norway. The conference has '
         b'also been previously known as <a href="http://www-rocq.inria.fr/arle'
         b's/events/iTrust2005/">iTrust</a>. Next year, PST and IFIPTM split ag'
         b'ain, as PST returns to its roots as a local event in Canada; next ye'
         b'ar, IFIPTM is organized in the US, and in Japan after that. We&#8217'
         b';ve summarized IFIPTM workshops on <a href="http://mobblog.cs.ucl.ac'
         b'.uk/2008/06/23/ifiptm-monday-workshops-cat-w2trust/">Monday</a> and '
         b'<a href="http://mobblog.cs.ucl.ac.uk/2008/06/18/intl-workshop-on-tru'
         b'st-in-mobile-environments/">Tuesday</a> in earlier posts, and now gi'
         b've a quick run-through of what <a href="http://www.ntnu.no/videre/ko'
         b'nferanse/IFIPTM08/program.html">this year&#8217;s conference program'
         b'</a> held.</p>\n<p style="0cm;"><span id="more-200"></span></p>\n<'
         b'p style="0cm;">Wednesday started with Peter Landrock&#8217;s keynote'
         b' on how to deal with and capture trust in the security sense. In the'
         b' first session on trust evaluation and management, we learned of <st'
         b'rong>TuLiP</strong> (Czenko, Doumen, Etalle), a policy language for '
         b'security credential trust management, saw a combination of logic and'
         b' probability theory to <strong>evaluate trust under uncertainty</str'
         b'ong> (Kohlas, Jonczy, Haenni), and got acquainted with <strong>Subje'
         b'ctive STAIRS</strong> (Refsdal, Solhaug, St\xc3\xb8len), an UML-ba'
         b'sed method to model the effects of (decision-making) policy.</p>'
         b'\n<p style="0cm;">The second session on trust and reputation mode'
         b'ls, started with a functional model of trust based on <a href="http:'
         b'//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intensional_logic" target="_self"><strong>in'
         b'tensional logic</strong></a> (Wan, Alagar; slight schedule reshuffle'
         b' there). The second presentation provided a simulation-based robustn'
         b'ess analysis of <strong>CertainTrust</strong> (Ries, Heinemann), a t'
         b'rust model for e.g. file exchange in opportunistic networks. The thi'
         b'rd presentation described and evaluated different strategies of shar'
         b'ing recommendations which are not directly interoperable, providing '
         b'some insight on <strong>how to translate recommendations</strong> (D'
         b'ondio, Longo, Barrett).</p>\n<p style="0cm;">The third session on'
         b' recommendation and reputation began with a model which <strong>comb'
         b'ines trust with user similarity</strong> (Pitsilis, Marshall) to pro'
         b'vide better recommendations. Neal presented a <strong>trust-based co'
         b'llaborative filtering</strong> (Lathia, Hailes, Capra) approach with'
         b' inspiration from trust and risk management. The third presentation '
         b'introduced <strong>SOFIA </strong>(Dell&#8217;Amico, Capra), a socia'
         b'l filtering system with extra robustness against <a href="http://en.'
         b'wikipedia.org/wiki/Sybil_attack">Sybil attacks</a>.</p>\n<p style'
         b'="0cm;">Thursday began with Stephan Engberg&#8217;s successfully pro'
         b'vocative, privacy-focused keynote on what we are forced to &#8220;tr'
         b'ust&#8221; and what we should actually be trusting. I&#8217;m still '
         b'fighting an urge to dive into an immediate sidetrack about personal '
         b'identification &#8211; thanks a bunch, Stephan.</p>\n<p>The fourt'
         b'h session returned to trust and reputation models. The first paper a'
         b'pplied <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fuzzy_logic" target="_s'
         b'elf">fuzzy logic</a> membership functions to <a href="http://en.wiki'
         b'pedia.org/wiki/Subjective_logic" target="_self">subjective logic</a>'
         b' in order to support <strong>continuous ratings in Bayesian reputati'
         b'on systems</strong> (J\xc3\xb8sang, Luo, Chen). The second paper p'
         b'resented a recommender clique, or <strong>knot-aware reputation mode'
         b'l</strong> (Gal-Oz, Gudes, Hendler), which pleasantly reminded me of'
         b' <a href="http://doi.acm.org/10.1145/544741.544854">REGRET</a>. The '
         b'third presentation dove into consumer behaviour and attribute prefer'
         b'ences to build the <strong>North Laine Shopping Guide</strong> (Robi'
         b'nson, Wakeman, Chalmers, Basu). Fourth, we enjoyed a game-theoretica'
         b'l simulation approach of an iterated prisoner&#8217;s dilemma with e'
         b'xperience-gathering, to study <strong>cooperation in growing communi'
         b'ties</strong> (Martin-Hughes).</p>\n<p style="0cm;">The fifth ses'
         b'sion on privacy and applications started with a model for reasoning '
         b'about the <strong>privacy impact of composite pervasive services</st'
         b'rong> (Cardoso, Issarny) based on <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w'
         b'iki/Fuzzy_cognitive_map" target="_self">fuzzy cognitive maps</a>: th'
         b'ere&#8217;s a difference between providing information to a single l'
         b'arge service and dividing it between a set of partial services. The '
         b'second paper was an interesting look into how to <strong>obfuscate y'
         b'our location</strong> (Damiani, Bertino, Silvestri) from a service p'
         b'rovider who needs the information to provide you a high-quality serv'
         b'ice. It turns out there is a lot that can be done there too. The thi'
         b'rd presentation proposed a <strong><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/'
         b'wiki/Folksonomy" target="_self">folksonomy</a>-based collaborative d'
         b'atabase</strong> (Buchmann, B\xc3\xb6hm, Raabe) to keep track of o'
         b'rganizations, locations (e.g. cameras) etc. that invade data privacy'
         b'.</p>\n<p style="0cm;">The day ended in a panel session about <st'
         b'rong>software as a service</strong>. The challenges seemed to outwei'
         b'gh the opportunities. However, the loss of control over data, securi'
         b'ty and availability does not seem to discourage companies from longi'
         b'ng after software that someone else upkeeps.</p>\n<p style="0cm;"'
         b'>Friday&#8217;s sixth session was on cryptography. In the first pape'
         b'r, applied <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pi-calculus" target'
         b'="_self">pi calculus</a> was put to use in <strong>automatically ver'
         b'ifying privacy properties</strong> (Delaune, Ryan, Smyth). The secon'
         b'd presentation provided an interesting certification approach to <st'
         b'rong>place and time authentication for cultural assets</strong> (Mos'
         b'tarda, Dong, Dulay). The third paper focused on efficiently <strong>'
         b'ensuring authenticity of binaries in Windows </strong>(Halim, Ramnat'
         b'h, Sufatrio, Wu, Yap).</p>\n<p style="0cm;">The seventh session b'
         b'egan with a refreshing extension to existing Web Services standards '
         b'in order to support <strong>credential-based trust negotiation</stro'
         b'ng> (Lee, Winslett). The second presentation continued on the policy'
         b' track, on <strong>assigning responsibility for failed obligations</'
         b'strong> (Irwin, Yu, Winsborough) which in turn can lead to other obl'
         b'igations failing due to interdependencies. The third paper presented'
         b' a multilevel identity management scheme to <strong>ensure privacy w'
         b'hile upkeeping accountability</strong> (Anwar, Greer) in the context'
         b' of E-Learning.</p>\n<p style="0cm;">The demo session presented t'
         b'wo systems besides the <a href="http://mobblog.cs.ucl.ac.uk/2008/06/'
         b'20/get-ready-to-rummble/" target="_self">earlier-mentioned Rummble</'
         b'a> (Cox). The second was a policy expression and enforcement system '
         b'for <strong>selectively &#8220;sandboxing&#8221; mobile .NET softwar'
         b'e</strong> (Dragoni, Massacci, Naliuka), e.g. to not be able to use '
         b'expensive services like phone calls for more than a certain amount p'
         b'er session. The third presented <strong>STORE, a stochastic reputati'
         b'on service for virtual organizations</strong> (Haller). The basic id'
         b'ea is to use global monitoring and storage to provide actually measu'
         b'rable quality of service information. And then spice it up with some'
         b' fuzzy feelings of fulfilment.</p>\n<p style="0cm;">Are we out of'
         b' breath yet?</p>\n<p style="0cm;">My three thoroughly <a href="ht'
         b'tp://mobblog.cs.ucl.ac.uk/2008/04/30/cinco-supporting-trust-decision'
         b's-for-inter-enterprise-collaboration/" target="_self">CINCO-biased</'
         b'a> and hopefully  recommendations from the conference would be: 1) R'
         b'efsdal et al&#8217;s Subjective STAIRS, since this sort of modelling'
         b' takes us a step closer to having the information available for auto'
         b'mated decision-making as well. 2) Dondio et al&#8217;s recommendatio'
         b'n translation work, because we need to be putting thought into recom'
         b'mendation interoperability to not forever keep producing incompatibl'
         b'e islets of information (i.e. the Not Invented Here approach). And 3'
         b') Haller&#8217;s STORE, because while I don&#8217;t believe in globa'
         b'l trusted monitors, I expect businesses won&#8217;t uncritically emb'
         b'race the idea of random other organizations expressing what they thi'
         b'nk of them on a highly subjective scale &#8211; rather, at least som'
         b'e measures ought to be relatively objectively measurable. So, now we'
         b' just need to hack our way around global monitoring. Receipts, anyon'
         b'e?</p>\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t<p class="postmetadata alt"'
